<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Mary Stewart: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="RSC" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 June 1999</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 December 1999</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily orgName and bibCit cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DRG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 February 2001</DATE><ITEM>converted textual apostrophes and quotation marks to entity references</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SLB" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2002</DATE><ITEM>removed title tag(s) from workscited</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 April 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily PLACE cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily TGENRENAME cleanup, BIBCIT following P moved before P, BIBCITS TAG added</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>08 April 2005</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: March 2005 Specifications. Mainly tag/attribute name changes</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 June 2005</DATE><ITEM>mangled</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>6 June 2007</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>25 July 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>15 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>23 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>24 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>26 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 August 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 September 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>10 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DEL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>21 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DEL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>21 October 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>4 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>checked in on behalf of DEL</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 November 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>27 November 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft p, rbv p</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>1 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>1 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>6 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c, cft c, pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>15 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>15 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>15 December 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>16 December 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c pilot43</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Stewart, Mary</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P><GENERICRANGE>MS, who began publishing in the mid 1950s, has won great success as an author of <TGENRE GENRENAME="POPULAR">popular</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romance</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">thrillers</TGENRE> and of <NAME STANDARD="Arthur, King">Arthurian</NAME> <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE>. She has also written <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">for children</TGENRE>.</GENERICRANGE> The suspense books of her early and mid career are mostly set against the beautiful backdrop of some tourist destination, and a sense of place is brilliantly conveyed. The Arthurian books are darker and their violence more pervasive.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Early Writing</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Mary Rainbow (later MS) began writing at an early age. She later commented that  <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I believe I could put words on paper when I was a little over three years old.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 562" DBREF="68970">562</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>At around five or six she published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY"><TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA">poem</TGENRE></TGENRE>, entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Teeth</TITLE>, in the parish magazine edited by her father.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 2" DBREF="68611" QTDIN="QTDINYES">2</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 3" DBREF="68785">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY> The only other poem which MS remembers from this time was about a <TTHEMETOPIC>horse</TTHEMETOPIC> called Dawn. <PPERFORMANCE>She notes:<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">at intervals I was required to recite it in public, which I did with great pride.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 3" DBREF="68785">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERFORMANCE> By the time she was seven years old, she had written a book of <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poems</TGENRE> and had filled several exercise books with <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA"><TGENRE GENRENAME="FAIRYTALE">fairy stories</TGENRE></TGENRE> and animal stories.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 562-3" DBREF="68970">562-3</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 3" DBREF="68785">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> These early stories took three <TTHEMETOPIC>toy animals</TTHEMETOPIC> (who were also their audience) as their main characters: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a little rubber horse, a tin elephant, and a small rubber cat that whistled when you pressed it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 562" DBREF="68970">562</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>In addition to writing stories, Mary Rainbow also illustrated them. In fact, drawing was her first ambition. She later remarked that she <RSELFDESCRIPTION><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">would draw my stories, then write to match the pictures. I think I took the writing part of it very much for granted.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 563" DBREF="68970">563</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PNONSURVIVAL TYPEOFNONSURVIVAL="UNKNOWN">Her mother kept her book of poems, but what she considers the best of her early work, an illustrated book of <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA"><TGENRE GENRENAME="FAIRYTALE">fairy tales</TGENRE></TGENRE>, was lost.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 563" DBREF="68970">563</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONSURVIVAL></RSELFDESCRIPTION></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>While studying at the <ORGNAME>University of Durham</ORGNAME>  Mary Rainbow (later MS) continued to write, but <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE> rather than fiction, <PMOTIVES>with the dream of becoming a lecturer on poetry at Oxford.</PMOTIVES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 3" DBREF="68611">3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>Later, when she was lecturing at Durham, she published some of her poetry in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">University of Durham Journal</TITLE>.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>It was only after her marriage and subsequent ectopic pregnancy that MS began seriously to consider writing <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE>. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="IMITATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">In <DATE>1948</DATE> she began work on a <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s story</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Enchanted Journey</TITLE>, which was inspired by <NAME STANDARD="De la Mare, Walter">Walter de la Mare</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Henry Brocken</TITLE>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><TGENREISSUE>Stewart submitted the manuscript to a number of British publishers but they rejected it on the basis that it was <TTONESTYLE>too frightening for a <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s tale</TGENRE>.</TTONESTYLE></TGENREISSUE></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Off the Page" DBREF="68978"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wilson Library Bulletin 35 (December 1960): 328" DBREF="68765">35 (December 1960): 328</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xiv" DBREF="68611">xiv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>First Novel</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Madam, Will You Talk?</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106213" PLACEHOLDER="MS, Madam, Will You Talk?, 1954"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1955-02-25" CERTAINTY="BY">Late 1954 or early 1955</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, the <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">thriller</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Madam, Will You Talk?</TITLE> The date is given by some sources as 1954 and by some as 1955.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">British Library Catalogue</TITLE> suggests that this book was published in 1955 with 1954 on the title-page.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">This work was serialized in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Woman&apos;s Journal</TITLE> before book publication.</PSERIALIZATION> <PPLACEOFPUBLICATION><PEDITIONS>An <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">American</GEOG></PLACE> edition appeared in 1955.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2769 (25 February 1955): 124" DBREF="54246">2769 (25 February 1955): 124</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></PPLACEOFPUBLICATION> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION">MS took her title from a folk-song which runs: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Madam, will you walk? / Madam, will you talk? / Madam, will you walk and talk with me?</QUOTE> (which she quotes at the head of chapter 15).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stewart, Three Novels 95" DBREF="69846">95</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>The novel, which she began in 1951 under the title <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Madam, Will You Talk?">Murder for Charity</TITLE>, took two years to write.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="FAMILIAL">She did not seriously consider sending it to a publisher until her <NAME STANDARD="Stewart, Sir Frederick Henry">husband</NAME> urged that it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">might as well be out of the house as in it</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 8" DBREF="68785">8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PINFLUENCESHER> <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>She then sent it to several publishers who turned it down, but their comments did her a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">power of good.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stewart, News" DBREF="69146"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She re-wrote and re-named it, discarding the last third of the story in the process, and then submitted the manuscript to <ORGNAME>Hodder and Stoughton</ORGNAME>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stewart, News" DBREF="69146"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><PCONTRACT>On <DATE VALUE="1953-12-24">Christmas Eve, 1953</DATE>, a contract for <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Madam, Will You Talk?</TITLE> from <ORGNAME>Hodder and Stoughton</ORGNAME> arrived in the post.</PCONTRACT><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2769 (25 February 1955): 124" DBREF="54246">2769 (25 February 1955): 124</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xiv" DBREF="68611">xiv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>John Attenborough</NAME> took on the position of MS&apos;s agent as well as that of her publisher at <ORGNAME>Hodder and Stoughton</ORGNAME>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Brown, The Independent, (14 May 1994)" DBREF="68850">(14 May 1994)</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PADVERTISING>Hodder did her first book proud, with an advertisement on the front page of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> that used the language of horse-racing to forecast Stewart&apos;s future success, and quoted big names in crime writing&mdash;<NAME STANDARD="Du Maurier, Daphne">Daphne Du Maurier</NAME>, <NAME>Margery Allingham</NAME>, <NAME>Patricia Wentworth</NAME>, and <NAME>Victor Canning</NAME>&mdash;in praise of her first novel.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2769 (25 February 1955): 124" DBREF="54246">2769 (25 February 1955): 124</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PADVERTISING></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT">The novel is set in southern France: the action begins in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Avignon</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> and concludes in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Marseilles</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Epigraphs to chapters range through the traditional English literary canon&mdash;<NAME STANDARD="Chaucer, Geoffrey">Chaucer</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Spenser, Edmund">Spenser</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>, <NAME>Robert Browning</NAME>, and so on&mdash;plus songs and proverbs from several languages, and stage directions (like <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Re-enter Murderer</QUOTE>)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stewart, Three Novels 81" DBREF="69846">81</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TGENREISSUE>which give the <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">story</TGENRE> the feel of a <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">drama</TGENRE>.</TGENREISSUE></TINTERTEXTUALITY> The heroine, <TCHARACTERNAME>Charity Selbourne</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">young widow</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, arrives in Avignon on holiday and befriends a young boy called <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Byron, David">David</TCHARACTERNAME> who is staying at the hotel with his stepmother, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Byron, Loraine">Loraine</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>beautiful but secretive</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> woman. Charity soon discovers that David&apos;s father is <TCHARACTERNAME>Richard Byron</TCHARACTERNAME>, a man who has been suspected of <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">murdering</TMOTIF> his best friend, <TCHARACTERNAME>Tony Baxter</TCHARACTERNAME>, but who was acquitted for lack of evidence. Richard, as Charity subsequently learns, is in France attempting to find his son. Believing that David is terrified of being found by his father, Charity decides to help the boy as best she can.</P><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"> In a chance encounter with Richard Byron while sight-seeing in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>N&icirc;mes</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>,</TSETTINGPLACE> Charity finds herself the object of Richard&apos;s attention as he hunts her down to discover David&apos;s whereabouts. A tense and exciting <TTHEMETOPIC>car chase</TTHEMETOPIC> through southern France follows as Charity believes herself hunted by a madman and a murderer. Richard eventually catches up with her in Marseilles and she discovers that he is not in fact a murderer, despite her initial impression of his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">brooding bitterness, and [the] unpleasant set to [his] mouth.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Madam, 54" DBREF="69147">54</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Someone has framed him for Tony&apos;s murder, and when that failed has made several attempts on his life. Richard suspects that Loraine is involved, but does not know why he, an ordinary <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">antique dealer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, has been targeted.</P><P>Pieces of the <TMOTIF>mystery</TMOTIF> reveal themselves as the characters encounter each other in Marseilles. It turns out that Loraine was already married to a Frenchman before she met Richard, and that they are both employed by <TCHARACTERNAME>Kramer</TCHARACTERNAME>, a shady <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>antique dealer, smuggler, and ex-Nazi</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who had committed murder during the war, an event that Richard (and Tony) had witnessed while they were prisoners of war.</P><P>Through a series of coincidental events, both Richard and David (who has run away from Loraine and made his way to Marseilles) end up kidnapped by Kramer. Charity attempts to secure help from another guest at the hotel, <TCHARACTERNAME>Paul V&eacute;ry</TCHARACTERNAME>, but he turns out to be Loraine&apos;s husband and Kramer&apos;s accomplice. A final action-filled climax involves a <TTHEMETOPIC>race against time</TTHEMETOPIC> on the dark highway outside Marseilles, the revelation of  Paul&apos;s identity, the rescue of Richard and David, and the discovery that <TCHARACTERNAME>Marsden</TCHARACTERNAME>, a shady character who has made several appearances earlier in the novel, actually  works for <ORGNAME STANDARD="Scotland Yard">Scotland Yard</ORGNAME>. The villains of the novel are all tidily dealt with as Paul, attempting to warn Kramer and Loraine, speeds out into the dark highway and collides with their oncoming car, propelling both cars off a cliff. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy ending">For Richard and Charity, the novel ends happily.</TMOTIF> Having fallen in love during the three days they have known each other, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="marriage ending">they decide to get married nine days later and the novel ends with them <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">heading off for their honeymoon in the beautiful southern <PLACE><GEOG REG="France">French</GEOG> island of <REGION>Porquerolles</REGION></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE></TMOTIF></P><P><TGENREISSUE><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Madam, Will You Talk?</TITLE> was the first of MS&apos;s many bestsellers whose genre has been the subject of debate among critics. They have been variously defined as <TGENRE GENRENAME="MYSTERY">mysteries</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">thrillers</TGENRE>, and <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romances</TGENRE>. MS comments that she calls them <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><QUOTE DIRECT="N">thrillers</QUOTE> for want of a better word, but it isn&apos;t the one I like.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 564" DBREF="68970">564</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She does not like (and nor did <NAME>Roy Newquist</NAME>) calling them mysteries or <TGENRE GENRENAME="DETECTIVE">detective</TGENRE> stories.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 562, 564" DBREF="68970">562, 564</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PATTITUDES>She prefers to call her novels <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fast-moving stories that entertain,</QUOTE> since <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><QUOTE DIRECT="N">Storyteller</QUOTE> is an old and honorable title, and I&apos;d like to lay claim to it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 564" DBREF="68970">564</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></TGENREISSUE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">This novel was welcomed by fellow novelists. <PADVERTISING>In the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Times Literary Supplement">TLS</TITLE> advertisement that heralded it, <NAME STANDARD="Du Maurier, Daphne">Daphne du Maurier</NAME> called it a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">brave start</QUOTE> and <NAME>Patricia Wentworth</NAME> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a delightful work; cultured and charming, besides being very exciting.</QUOTE> <NAME>Margery Allingham</NAME> referred to it as a romantic thriller <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in the classic tradition,</QUOTE> whose <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">excellent English makes it delightfully easy to read.</QUOTE> <NAME>Victor Canning</NAME> noted that it had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">pace, a blessedly readable style, and the kind of suspense that makes you sit forward, and it gallops through to a good finish. A thoroughbred among thrillers.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2769 (25 February 1955): 124" DBREF="54246">2769 (25 February 1955): 124</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PADVERTISING> Some reviewers noted shortcomings. <NAME>Anthony Boucher</NAME>, writing for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New York Times, The">New York Times</TITLE>, complained of implausibility in the plot, commenting that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a backward glance will reveal so many whopping coincidences and inadequate or inconsistent motivations that you can&apos;t believe a word of it.</QUOTE> However, he admitted that because MS was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">so unusually skillful . . . in her first novel . . . you don&apos;t really care.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Boucher, New York Times, (18 March 1956): 267" DBREF="69148">(18 March 1956): 267</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">More recently <NAME>Nora Roberts</NAME>, herself a best-seller, commented that this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">little jewel of a book, blending romance and suspense, will tell future generations that many of us believed, despite all evidence to the contrary, that love conquers all.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mukherjee, New York Times Capsule, Words" DBREF="69845" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><PNONBOOKMEDIA>The novel was made into an audio book on cassette in 1985 and released in CD form in 2010.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONBOOKMEDIA></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>More Suspense Novels</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">MS followed <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Madam, Will You Talk?</TITLE> with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Wildfire at Midnight</TITLE> (a <TGENRE GENRENAME="DETECTIVE">detective</TGENRE> story set on the Hebridean island of <PLACE><REGION>Skye</REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>, 1956), and then <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Thunder on the Right</TITLE> (set in the <PLACE><REGION>Pyrenees</REGION><AREA REG="Europe"></AREA></PLACE>, 1957).</TSETTINGPLACE> This was actually the second novel she wrote, but it was published third.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 14, 17" DBREF="68611">14, 17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RSELFDESCRIPTION><TTONESTYLE>It was her least favourite novel, on which she later said she had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">splurged with adjectives, all colored purple.</QUOTE></TTONESTYLE> Indeed, she said it was a book she would <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">like to see . . . drowned beyond recovery.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 569" DBREF="68970">569</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION>In <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Wildfire at Midnight</TITLE> she attempted something quite different from her first two books: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the classic closed-room detective story with restricted action, a biggish cast, and a closely circular plot.</QUOTE> This taught her a lot technically, but also convinced her that in the long run the <TGENRE GENRENAME="DETECTIVE">detective</TGENRE> novel was not her genre.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Stewart website" DBREF="69825" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Nine Coaches Waiting</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69848" PLACEHOLDER="MS, Nine Coaches Waiting, 1958"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1958-11-28" CERTAINTY="BY">By late November 1958</DATE><CHRONPROSE>The fourth <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> by MS, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Nine Coaches Waiting</TITLE>, was a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">governess</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> novel, which has drawn comparisons with <NAME STANDARD="Du Maurier, Daphne">Daphne du Maurier</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Rebecca</TITLE> and <NAME>Charlotte Bront&euml;</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Jane Eyre</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 2961 (28 November 1958): 684" DBREF="54246">2961 (28 November 1958): 684</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 19" DBREF="68611">19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">The novel was abridged for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Ladies&apos; Home Journal</TITLE> during 1958,</PSERIALIZATION> <PEDITIONS><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>the year before book publication in the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE>.</PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PEDITIONS> <PDEDICATION>It is dedicated to <NAME>Elizabeth Manners</NAME>.</PDEDICATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 178" DBREF="69308">178</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The title phrase comes from a temptation speech in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Revenger&apos;s Tragedy</TITLE>, designed to lure a naive young girl towards the delights of being wealthy and sought-after.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 181, 184-5" DBREF="69308">181, 184-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Stewart credited <NAME STANDARD="Tourneur, Cyril">Tourneur</NAME> as author of this play. It is now generally ascribed to <NAME STANDARD="Middleton, Thomas,, 1580 - 1627">Middleton</NAME>.</P></SCHOLARNOTE> Each chapter (headed as before with quotations from English literature) equates to a coach or coaches.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TSETTINGPLACE>The story opens as <TCHARACTERNAME>Linda Martin</TCHARACTERNAME>, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">part-English, part-French protagonist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, arrives in Paris, on the way to southern <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE>, where most of the action takes place.</TSETTINGPLACE> She has taken a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">governess</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> job in a rich family that requires her to speak English, but after a happy though deprived childhood in wartime France and some bleak, best-forgotten years in England, she feels a necessity for professional reasons to suppress the French side of her personality. Stewart describes this as a novel built around a complex core, which required very careful thinking through.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 570" DBREF="68970">570</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Linda&apos;s eventual beloved, Raoul, appears for a long time to be a dastardly character, and she experiences a time of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the world gone mad and values shot to smithereens</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 429" DBREF="69308">429</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> before the eventual <TMOTIF>happy ending</TMOTIF>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Lenemaja Friedman</NAME> claimed this as the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">most complete and best of [MS&apos;s] suspense novels.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 19" DBREF="68611">19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Greece: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">My Brother Michael</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69308" PLACEHOLDER="MS, My Brother Michael, 1960"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1960-02-26" CERTAINTY="BY">By late February 1960</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">MS published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">My Brother Michael</TITLE>, the first of her <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">suspense</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> to have a <PLACE><GEOG REG="Greece">Greek</GEOG></PLACE> setting.</TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3026 (26 February 1960): 133" DBREF="54246">3026 (26 February 1960): 133</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>MS wrote <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">My Brother Michael</TITLE> after she had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">visited <PLACE><GEOG REG="Greece">Greece</GEOG></PLACE> two or three times, and was wildly in love with it.</QUOTE></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PMOTIVES>She <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">longed to set a book there, to re-create certain places for myself and other people.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 566" DBREF="68970">566</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMOTIVES> An author&apos;s note thanks all those who gave MS help while she was in Greece, <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">as well as identifying the translations used of <NAME>Sophocles</NAME>, <NAME>Euripides</NAME>, <NAME>Aristophanes</NAME>, and <NAME>Aristotle</NAME>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The book as a whole has an epigraph from <NAME>Rex Warner</NAME>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">If you do not love the Greeks, you cannot love anything.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 434" DBREF="69308" QTDIN="QTDINYES">434</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT">The novel begins in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Athens</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE>, where the heroine, <TCHARACTERNAME>Camilla Haven</TCHARACTERNAME>, is on holiday. Desiring to visit <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Delphi</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE>, she is too short of money to rent a car to drive there and resigns herself to a one-day bus tour.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> In an unexpected turn of events Camilla, to whom <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[n]othing ever happens,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 435" DBREF="69308">435</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> is mistaken for someone else and ends up in Delphi with a car meant for a <SOCALLED>Monsieur Simon</SOCALLED>, on an apparent <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">matter of life and death.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 438" DBREF="69308">438</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> When no one arrives to claim the car, Camilla decides to accept this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">intervention of providence,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Three Novels 443" DBREF="69308">443</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> drive it to Delphi herself, and return it to this Monsieur Simon.</P><P><TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">On her way to Delphi, she has some difficulty backing the car in a village called <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Arachova</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Boeotia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE>: she reverses into a shop doorway and into a donkey. In this situation, <TCHARACTERNAME>Simon Lester</TCHARACTERNAME>, an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">English classics teacher</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who is visiting Greece, comes to her <TMOTIF>rescue</TMOTIF>. They drive into Delphi together and Camilla eventually discovers that Simon is in Greece not for a holiday but to learn about his brother Michael&apos;s death fourteen years before, during the <TOPIC>second world war</TOPIC>, near <PLACE><REGION>Mount Parnassus</REGION><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> From a letter that Michael wrote just before he died, Simon suspects that some <TMOTIF>mystery</TMOTIF> was involved. It turns out, over the approach to a frightening climax, that Simon is right. Michael discovered a trove of <TTHEMETOPIC>ancient gold coins</TTHEMETOPIC>; he was <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">murdered</TMOTIF>. In the present time of the book two more people are murdered before the murderer is struck down by retribution of the kind once meted out by the Furies, and not only Simon but also Camilla learns how possible it is, in the last resort, to kill.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> judged the novel more conventional than others reviewed with it. It complained that the hero and heroine were both merely <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">decent</QUOTE> (although the unsuspected capacity of decent people is, surely, Stewart&apos;s precise point), but it warmed to the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">zestful . . . brio</QUOTE> of the climactic <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">set-to between hero and villain.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3026 (26 February 1960): 133" DBREF="54246">3026 (26 February 1960): 133</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRECOGNITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">My Brother Michael</TITLE> earned the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>British Crime Writers Association Silver Dagger Award</RRECOGNITIONNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA online" DBREF="16185"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS> According to Friedman <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">it is often mentioned by readers, along with the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ivy Tree</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Moon-Spinners</TITLE>, as their favourite works by MS.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 26" DBREF="68611">26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ivy Tree</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69849" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Ivy Tree, 1961"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1961 MS published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Ivy Tree</TITLE>, the first of her <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> with a setting in Britain and one of her most <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">suspenseful</TGENRE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The protagonist of this novel <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">comes from Canada to visit <PLACE><REGION>Northumberland</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> seeking her family&apos;s roots.</TSETTINGPLACE> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="mistaken identity">She finds herself being mistaken for a distant relation, a beautiful woman now dead,</TMOTIF> who was positioned at the heart of an <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">inheritance battle</TMOTIF>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Friedman, Lenemaja">Friedman</NAME> has called this book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a masterpiece of reader manipulation</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 30" DBREF="68611">30</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRECOGNITIONS>It won the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Crime Writers Association Silver Dagger</RRECOGNITIONNAME>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xiv" DBREF="68611">xiv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>More Settings: Greece, Austria, Lebanon</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>MS published two more <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> with Greek settings: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Moon-Spinners</TITLE> (1962) and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">This Rough Magic</TITLE> (1964). <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">The former, whose very young heroine is called Nicola, begins in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Athens</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE> and ends in <PLACE><REGION>Crete</REGION><GEOG REG="Greece"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>Its author was particularly fond of it, but calls it episodic.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 571, 570" DBREF="68970">571, 570</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION> <PNONBOOKMEDIA>It was made into a movie by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Walt Disney Company">Walt Disney</ORGNAME> in <DATE>1964</DATE>. (The film version, however, bears little resemblance to the novel.)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xiv" DBREF="68611">xiv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONBOOKMEDIA></P><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Airs Above the Ground</TITLE> (1965) is set in Austria: its plot involves the famous <TTHEMETOPIC>white Lipizzaner stallions which give displays of dressage at the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Spanish Riding School</PLACENAME> of <SETTLEMENT>Vienna</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Austria"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>. Two years later in 1967, MS published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gabriel Hounds</TITLE>, set in <PLACE><GEOG>Lebanon</GEOG></PLACE>, and in 1968 <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Wind off the Small Isles</TITLE>, set in <PLACE><REGION>Lanzarote</REGION></PLACE> in the <PLACE><REGION>Canary Islands</REGION></PLACE>,</TSETTINGPLACE> <TCHARACTERIZATION>where the central couple (both English) are the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">secretary to a famous children&apos;s writer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">research assistant to a famous playwright</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</TCHARACTERIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">For MS, setting is crucial to her storytelling and she prefers to have the story set out of doors. For most of her novels the settings provided the starting point for her writing; they were, she states, a means to<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">recreate something particularly beautiful or with a history that interested me </QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Off the Page" DBREF="68978"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> This means that her extensive, lifelong travelling has often sparked her desire to write in order to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">revisit that place</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Off the Page" DBREF="68978"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Characters emerged during the writing process in relation to the setting. As MS herself commented: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">you shove a few people in [to the setting] and let them get on with it</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Off the Page" DBREF="68978"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></PATTITUDES> <TTECHNIQUES>Visual description is an important part of Stewart&apos;s art.</TTECHNIQUES></P><P>Themes which made an initial appearance in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Madam, Will You Talk?</TITLE> often recur in varying forms in her later suspense novels. These include a <TTHEMETOPIC>chase scene</TTHEMETOPIC>, <TCHARACTERIZATION>a heroine (usually English) who is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">off vacationing in an exciting part of the world,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 116" DBREF="68611">116</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> a villain who is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">often <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>charming, handsome, and on the surface reliable</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 116" DBREF="68611">116</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and a hero who <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">seems to be evil, because he is often a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">mysterious, shadowy figure with questionable motives</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, all of which are clearly understood and found worthy by the end of the story.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 117" DBREF="68611">117</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION">In her earlier novels MS heads her chapters with literary quotations.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">This Rough Magic</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69850" PLACEHOLDER="MS, This Rough Magic, 1964"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>1964</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RBESTKNOWNWORK><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">MS set her <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">This Rough Magic</TITLE> on the <PLACE><GEOG REG="Greece">Greek</GEOG> island of <REGION REG="Corfu">Corfu</REGION></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE></RBESTKNOWNWORK></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xiv" DBREF="68611">xiv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>She wrote this over nearly two years, because of interruptions, in a mysterious process which she likens to hanging a thread in an alum solution and waiting for crystals to form.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 566" DBREF="68970">566</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The title comes from <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>&apos;s Prospero, in the speech in which he abjures his magic and breaks his staff.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">It plays on a traditional identification of the island of Corfu with the mysterious island where <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME> set <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tempest</TITLE>. In Stewart&apos;s story it is very different from the Greek mainland or other islands, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[m]uch richer, beautiful in a fertile, flowering sort of way.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 570" DBREF="68970">570</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> There such happenings as <TTHEMETOPIC>making friends with a dolphin</TTHEMETOPIC> appear to be not quite of this world. The story features a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>controlling power-figure</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Sir Julian Gale</TCHARACTERNAME>, a theatre knight from England who is renting an improbable castle on the island.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRECOGNITIONS>This book was awarded the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Mystery Writers of America Edgar Award</RRECOGNITIONNAME> (named after <NAME>Edgar Allan Poe</NAME>) <PCIRCULATION>and stayed on the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New York Times, The">New York Times</TITLE> best-seller list for eight months.</PCIRCULATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA online" DBREF="16185"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xiv" DBREF="68611">xiv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Radio Plays</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>26 August 1958</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERFORMANCE>One of MS&apos;s four <TGENRE GENRENAME="RADIODRAMA">radio plays</TGENRE> written this year (or this and the previous year), <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lift from a Stranger</TITLE>, was broadcast on <ORGNAME>BBC</ORGNAME> radio.</PPERFORMANCE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 127" DBREF="68611">127</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA online" DBREF="16185"></BIBCIT><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: there seems to be some discrepancy in terms of what year they were aired. Friedman says 1958, CA says 1957-8. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Scottish Writing and Writers</TITLE> says 1957 for <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lift from a Stranger</TITLE> and 1958 for the rest of the plays: hence wording of the chronprose.</RESEARCHNOTE></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><TGENREISSUE>Despite her prolific output of <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE>, Stewart later claimed that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I have always been rather more interested in <TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">dramatic form</TGENRE> than in the novel</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wilson Library Bulletin 35 (December 1960): 328" DBREF="68765" QTDIN="QTDINYES">35 (December 1960): 328</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE> Her other radio plays of about this date were <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Call Me at Ten-thirty</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Crime of Mr Merry</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Lord of Langdale</TITLE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lift from a Stranger</TITLE> features a girl who accepts a ride from a stranger on a country road at night.</TPLOT> The man, who is later revealed to be a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>homicide detective</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, talks <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">obsessively of a <TMOTIF>murder</TMOTIF></QUOTE> in order to frighten the girl so she will not again take car rides from strangers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Listener 60 (4 September 1958): 356" DBREF="2481">60 (4 September 1958): 356</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">A reviewer (<NAME>Ian Rodger</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Listener</TITLE>, who mistakenly called the author <SOCALLED>Miss Mary Stewart</SOCALLED>) noted that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the sensation of being in the car was powerfully evoked.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Listener 60 (4 September 1958): 356" DBREF="2481">60 (4 September 1958): 356</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Arthurian Novels</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING>Merlin Trilogy: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106214" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Crystal Cave, 1970"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1970-07-23" CERTAINTY="BY">By late July 1970</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RLANDMARKTEXT>MS published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE>, the first of her <TCHARACTERNAME>Merlin</TCHARACTERNAME> series of three <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE></TGENRE> and of a total of five <NAME><TCHARACTERNAME REG="Arthur, King">Arthurian</TCHARACTERNAME></NAME> books.</RLANDMARKTEXT></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3569 (23 July 1970): 833" DBREF="54246">3569 (23 July 1970): 833</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="LITERARY">Having always wanted to write a historical novel, MS later recalled that the idea for <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE> came from a story in an early <SOCALLED>history</SOCALLED> of <NAME>King Arthur</NAME>: <NAME STANDARD="Geoffrey of Monmouth">Geoffrey of Monmouth</NAME>&apos;s twelfth-century <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">History of the Kings of Britain</TITLE>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thompson" DBREF="68976"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 12" DBREF="68785">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> This incident featured the young Merlin&apos;s encounter with the British ruler or warlord <TCHARACTERNAME>Vortigern</TCHARACTERNAME>. MS found that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[e]ven in the formal prose of the <SOCALLED>history</SOCALLED> the story came through sharp and exciting&mdash;and human. Here was the story for me.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 12" DBREF="68785">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PINFLUENCESHER> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><TGENREISSUE>Initially her publishers were concerned about this shift in genre; they would have preferred her to continue writing the <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">suspense novels</TGENRE> which had proved to be financially successful, rather than take on the territory of <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">Dark Ages history</TGENRE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thompson" DBREF="68976"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PATTITUDES>MS, however, notes that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I had to write for myself. And if the time was not right and the readers didn&apos;t want the change, then it would be a flop. But I wouldn&apos;t have changed one jot of it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Carson, Globe and Mail, (14 June 1973): W3" DBREF="68974">(14 June 1973): W3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> Despite her publisher&apos;s anxieties, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE> proved to be just as popular as her other works, and it is her books about Merlin and King Arthur for which she is now best known.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">Rather than set <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE> in medieval Britain (which is sometimes used for Arthurian stories but which as a period had never appealed to her) MS set it in fifth-century Roman Britain.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thompson" DBREF="68976"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGDATE> <TVOICENARRATION>The story, narrated by <TCHARACTERNAME>Merlin</TCHARACTERNAME> as an old man,</TVOICENARRATION> begins at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="Carmarthen" REG="Maridunum">Maridunum</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Carmarthenshire"></REGION> in <GEOG REG="Wales">South Wales</GEOG></PLACE> (the Roman settlement that later became Carmarthen) with <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Merlin">Myrddin Emrys</TCHARACTERNAME> (whom his mother calls Merlin) as a six-year-old boy. Although his grandfather is a king he is not treated like a prince, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="illegitimacy">his mother having conceived him while unmarried and claiming that his father was a prince of darkness</TMOTIF>. (Merlin later learns that his father is now the <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Ambrosius Aurelianus, King">High King Ambrosius</TCHARACTERNAME>&mdash;or Ambrosius Aurelianus&mdash;and that she had hidden him in a <TMOTIF>cave</TMOTIF> when he was an eighteen-year-old wounded enemy prince, giving him time to recover.)</P><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">One day while out riding, the boy Merlin makes the acquaintance of  <TCHARACTERNAME>Galapas</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>mystic</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who lives in the Crystal Cave  (the same cave in which Merlin was conceived).</TSETTINGPLACE> Galapas teaches Merlin about <TTHEMETOPIC>healing plants</TTHEMETOPIC> and cultivates the boy&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>gift of the second sight</TTHEMETOPIC>. It is in the Crystal Cave that Merlin sees the first of many <TTHEMETOPIC>visions</TTHEMETOPIC> of the past, present, and future.</P><P>On his grandfather&apos;s death Merlin flees from home, afraid that his <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Camlach">uncle Camlach</TCHARACTERNAME> may seize the opportunity to kill him. But he is captured by two of Ambrosius&apos;s spies, who take him to <PLACE><REGION CURRENT="Brittany" REG="Bretagne">Less Britain (what is now called in English Brittany)</REGION><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE>. There Merlin encounters his father, Ambrosius, and another uncle, <TCHARACTERNAME>Uther</TCHARACTERNAME>. Ambrosius recognizes him as his son and takes him under his protection.</P><P>When he is eighteen Merlin returns home to Wales to gather information for Ambrosius&apos; planned invasion. There he is captured by King Vortigern&apos;s men. Vortigern is building a fortress whose walls keep collapsing, and his priests claim that only the blood of one <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">who never had a father</QUOTE> will solve the problem. Merlin&apos;s alleged conception by a demon appears to provide them with a solution.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Crystal 302" DBREF="69149">302</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Through a combination of ingenuity and <TTHEMETOPIC>prophecy</TTHEMETOPIC>, Merlin avoids being killed and persuades Vortigern to abandon his fortress and return to his own land.</P><P>Ambrosius arrives in Britain and spends two years fighting to take control of the country. Merlin leaves the army and returns home after Ambrosius is crowned, but is later called back to rebuild the <PLACE><PLACENAME REG="Stonehenge">Giant&apos;s Dance (the stone circle now called Stonehenge)</PLACENAME><REGION REG="Wiltshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">strong symbol</QUOTE> under which Ambrosius will be buried as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the warrior under the threshold of all Britain.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Crystal 413" DBREF="69149">413</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>When Ambrosius dies, Uther becomes king. Smitten with love for the beautiful <TCHARACTERNAME>Ygrainne</TCHARACTERNAME>, wife of Glorlois, Uther calls on Merlin for help. Merlin, foreseeing that a child born to Ygrainne by Uther will be king, agrees to help Uther attain his desire. The novel ends with Arthur&apos;s conception at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Tintagel</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION REG="Cornwall">Cornwall</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</P><P>MS limits Merlin&apos;s magical abilities, providing ordinary explanations for many of his exploits, such as the raising of Stonehenge by engineering rather than supernatural means. Magic, instead, appears in the form of prophecy, which comes at <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the god&apos;s will</QUOTE> rather than Merlin&apos;s own.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Crystal 376" DBREF="69149">376</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE> was both a commercial and a critical success, <RRECOGNITIONS><PCIRCULATION>appearing on the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New York Times, The">New York Times</TITLE> best-seller list for ten months</PCIRCULATION> and <RRECOGNITIONNAME>selected by the <ORGNAME>Literary Guild</ORGNAME></RRECOGNITIONNAME>. It brought MS both the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Frederick Niven Literary Award</RRECOGNITIONNAME> and the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Mythopoeic Fantasy Award</RRECOGNITIONNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA online" DBREF="16185"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman xv" DBREF="68611">xv</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New York Times, The">New York Times</TITLE> review was positive, asserting that while <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[c]heerfully disclaiming authenticity, Mary Stewart . . . lightens the Dark Ages with legend, pure invention, and a lively sense of history.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (9 August 1970): 209" DBREF="16508">(9 August 1970): 209</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><PNONBOOKMEDIA>The novel was adapted for television in 1991 when the <ORGNAME STANDARD="BBC" REG="British Broadcasting Corporation">BBC</ORGNAME> filmed six episodes, which were then released together on video as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Merlin of the Crystal Cave</TITLE>. The series was directed by <NAME>Michael  Darlow</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Olton 99" DBREF="68988">99</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONBOOKMEDIA></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Merlin Trilogy: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Hollow Hills</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69851" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Hollow Hills, 1973"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>4 June 1973</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS published the second of her <NAME STANDARD="Arthur, King">Arthurian</NAME> <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Hollow Hills</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3707 (23 March 1973): 314" DBREF="54246">3707 (23 March 1973): 314</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">Although not at first intending to write a sequel to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">and thereby tread <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">on the same ground as <NAME>T. H. White</NAME> in his magnificent novel <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Sword in the Stone</TITLE>,</QUOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY> MS found that the idea of a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SEQUEL">sequel</TGENRE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">worked on in [her] imagination like yeast.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 13" DBREF="68785">13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMOTIVES> Determining that her sequel would be different in spirit and setting from White&apos;s novel, and having received many requests to continue her story, she says she found herself <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">almost in spite of myself . . . following my characters on after that wild night at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Tintagel</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Cornwall"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> when Arthur was conceived.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 12" DBREF="68785">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Hollow Hills</TITLE> begins where <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crystal Cave</TITLE> ended, and follows <TCHARACTERNAME>Merlin</TCHARACTERNAME> as he makes plans to keep <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Arthur, King">Arthur</TCHARACTERNAME> safe and secretly hidden until he has grown into manhood, mindful of the fact that he is the unacknowledged <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>future rightful king</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PCIRCULATION><PEARNINGS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Hollow Hills</TITLE> was one of the first books on which the<PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Russian Federation" REG="Russia">Soviet Union</GEOG></PLACE> paid royalities after joining the <ORGNAME>Universal Copyright Convention</ORGNAME> on <DATE VALUE="1973-05-27"> May 27, 1973</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Off the Page" DBREF="68978"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Maryles 390" DBREF="69826">390</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEARNINGS></PCIRCULATION></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Last Enchantment</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69852" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Last Enchantment, 1979"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1979-08-05" CERTAINTY="BY">By early August 1979</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS published her third book in the <TCHARACTERNAME>Merlin</TCHARACTERNAME> series of <NAME STANDARD="Arthur, King">Arthurian</NAME> <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Last Enchantment</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (5 August 1979): BR 6" DBREF="16508">(5 August 1979): BR 6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION>This book, narrated by Merlin in old age,</TVOICENARRATION> deals with the darker elements in the <SOCALLED>Matter of Britain</SOCALLED>, particularly <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Arthur, King">Arthur</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s fear of his enchantress half-sister <TCHARACTERNAME>Morgause</TCHARACTERNAME> and of the son she bore to him after she seduced him, <TCHARACTERNAME>Mordred</TCHARACTERNAME>. It opens with <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">shocking violence: Arthur&apos;s attempt to destroy the child Mordred by <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONUNACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE"><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of child">butchering all the district&apos;s children of his age</TMOTIF>, in the manner of <NAME STANDARD="Herod the Great,, King of Judaea">King Herod</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REND="normal">Bible</TITLE>.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></TMOTIF> Against the political achievements of Arthur&apos;s reign it sets not only this massacre of the innocents but also the various <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">betrayals of Arthur, especially that by his beloved queen</TMOTIF>. Merlin&apos;s own love-affair, however, is presented as one of bliss and fulfilment, even though on this occasion he is the object of enchantment and not its author.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">This novel was described as an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">adult&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="FAIRYTALE">fairytale</TGENRE></QUOTE> by the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New York Times, The">New York Times</TITLE> reviewer, <NAME>Martin Levin</NAME>. He called it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a perfect trip out of the present and into a dark but cozy age in which political problems can be settled by Excalibur and personal problems by <TMOTIF>witchcraft</TMOTIF>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Levin, New York Times (2 September 1979): BR3" DBREF="16508">(2 September 1979): BR3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Friedman, Lenemaja">Friedman</NAME>, on the other hand, thought this review superficial and unsatisfying.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 134" DBREF="68611">134</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><PNONBOOKMEDIA>Abridged adaptations of both <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Hollow Hills</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Last Enchantment</TITLE> appeared on audio cassettes in 1989, read by actor <NAME>Nicol Williamson</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONBOOKMEDIA></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Wicked Day</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106215" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Wicked Day, 1983"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1983-10-">October 1983</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Wicked Day</TITLE>, the fourth in her <NAME STANDARD="Arthur, King">Arthurian</NAME> <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">historical</TGENRE>-<TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> or <TGENRE GENRENAME="FANTASY">fantasy</TGENRE> series, with  <TCHARACTERNAME>Mordred</TCHARACTERNAME> as the central character.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 4202 (14 October 1983): 1109" DBREF="54246">4202 (14 October 1983): 1109</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION>This time she tells the story in the third person.</TVOICENARRATION> <TCHARACTERNAME>Merlin</TCHARACTERNAME> is present only as a very old man offstage, whose death is repeatedly rumoured before it happens. The book opens with Mordred as a baby about whom mysteries cluster, the cherished darling of his parents, or <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>foster parents, who are <PLACE><REGION REG="Orkney Islands">Orkney</REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE> peasant fisher folk</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. The woman, Sula, guesses that this child she loves is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">royal bastard</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, not fathered by the king, Lot, but borne by the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="female villain"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>charismatic and terrifying queen</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Morgause</TCHARACTERNAME> (implacable enemy of both Merlin and <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Arthur, King">Arthur</TCHARACTERNAME>)</TMOTIF>. The reader then meets Mordred as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">boy, hardy and self-reliant</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, before he meets the eldest of the queen&apos;s legitimate sons, <TCHARACTERNAME>Gawain</TCHARACTERNAME>, and is taken to live in the royal palace. As soon as she has him at court, Morgause ensures the foster-parents&apos; silence by <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">having their hovel burnt down</TMOTIF>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">their sleeping bodies in it</TMOTIF>. <TCHARACTERIZATION>Mordred&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>bewildered, stoical grief</TTHEMETOPIC>, amid his striving to find his feet in his baffling new world, ensure that for MS&apos;s reader he can never be merely the simple villain which he seems from his part in the story of his father King Arthur.</TCHARACTERIZATION> Indeed, when Morgause tells him that both she and Merlin in their different ways have foreseen that he will kill his father, he furiously denies it. By now he is in Arthur&apos;s service as his right-hand man.</P><P>Another stomach-turning piece of <TMOTIF>violence</TMOTIF>, more graphically described than the burning of Mordred&apos;s foster-parents, is the <TMOTIF>murder</TMOTIF> of <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">Morgause, fresh from the arms of one of her many younger lovers, by her son <TCHARACTERNAME>Gaheris</TCHARACTERNAME>, who has believed in her, and loves her, and goes berserk when he catches her <FOREIGN REG="in blazing" LANG="la">in flagrante</FOREIGN>.</TMOTIF> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The only sound was the soft and dreadful hacking of metal into flesh and feathered bedding. . . . . the naked body fell back into the merciful shadows. Less mercifully the head, half-severed, lolled into starlight on its blood-drenched pillows. Gaheris . . . with a howl like a hurt dog . . . put his head down beside his mother&apos;s and wept.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Wicked, US ed, 227" DBREF="70665">227</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The book is titled from the day of the last <TTHEMETOPIC>battle</TTHEMETOPIC>, when Mordred, now an open <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">challenger for the throne</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, mets with Arthur in <TTHEMETOPIC>single combat</TTHEMETOPIC> after almost all the knights are slain, and each gives the other his death-wound. MS sets it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[t]owards the end of the day, with [Arthur]&apos;s friends and long Companions dead or dying round him, and the hundreds of wasted deaths reeking to the now dark and threatening sky.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Wicked, US ed, 436" DBREF="70665">436</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE" SETTINGCLASS="UPPERCLASS">As the site of the battle she picks, with the support of modern archaelogical evidence, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>South Cadbury</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Wiltshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, a fortified hill now deep in the quiet countryside, beside the <PLACE><REGION REG="River Cam">River Cam or Camel</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>&mdash;a <PLACE><REGION>Somerset</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> river, not the River Camel in Cornwall<RESEARCHNOTE>img: n.b. we won&apos;t tag Cornwall: this little cluster of place tags shows nicely how complex Place can be!</RESEARCHNOTE> which is often claimed as the site of Arthur&apos;s last battle.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Wicked, US ed, 450-1" DBREF="70665">450-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Roy Hoffman</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New York Times, The">New York Times</TITLE> found <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Wicked Day</TITLE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[i]n almost every way . . . a  highly enjoyable romance.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Hoffman, New York Times (1 January 1984): BR20" DBREF="16508">(1 January 1984): BR20</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <PATTITUDES>Stewart herself apparently relished the irony of enrolling herself among those mentioned by <NAME>Edward Gibbon</NAME> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE">as derivative from ancient fables and fragments and hints about Dark Ages Britain: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">succeeding writers, whose works I am not ambitious either to censure or transcribe.</QUOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Wicked, US ed, 450" DBREF="70665" QTDIN="QTDINYES">450</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Prince and the Pilgrim</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69853" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Prince and the Pilgrim, 1995"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>2 November 1995</DATE><CHRONPROSE>For her final Arthurian <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Prince</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">Pilgrim</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></TITLE>, MS moved back from the <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORICAL">gruesome side of ancient history</TGENRE>, closer to the realm of <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romance</TGENRE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Blackwell" DBREF="579"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Of her two protagonists, <TCHARACTERNAME>Prince Alexander</TCHARACTERNAME> comes to <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Arthur, King">Arthur</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s court seeking <TTHEMETOPIC>vengeance</TTHEMETOPIC> for a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">murdered</TMOTIF> father, and Alice has been on <TTHEMETOPIC>pilgrimage to Jerusalem</TTHEMETOPIC> (with her father) and has come into contact with a a silver cup with supernatural properties, apparently the <TTHEMETOPIC>Holy Grail</TTHEMETOPIC> itself. A grimmer element in the story is provided by <TCHARACTERNAME>Morgan Le Fay</TCHARACTERNAME>, who wants to possess the Grail for use in <TTHEMETOPIC>black magic</TTHEMETOPIC>, but on the whole romance predominates.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Children&apos;s Books</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69310" PLACEHOLDER="MS, The Little Broomstick, 1971"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1971-10-22" CERTAINTY="BY">By 22 October 1971</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS issued her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Little Broomstick</TITLE>, <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>illustrated by <NAME>Shirley Hughes</NAME>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3634 (22 October 1971): 1316" DBREF="54246">3634 (22 October 1971): 1316</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Feminist Companion</TITLE> mistakenly identifies <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ludo and the Star Horse</TITLE> as MS&apos;s earliest work for children.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The protagonist, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">solitary child</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> called Mary, has some strange holiday experiences involving various elements of <TMOTIF>witchcraft</TMOTIF>: a black cat and a magic flower as well as the broomstick of the title, which combine to enable her to fly.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The reviewer for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> noted that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">it is not a perfect <TGENRE GENRENAME="FANTASY">fantasy</TGENRE> by any means. . . but there are, too, some moments of  real imaginative power.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3634 (22 October 1971): 1320" DBREF="54246">3634 (22 October 1971): 1320</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106212" PLACEHOLDER="MS, Ludo and the Star Horse, 1974"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>October 1974</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS published another <TGENRE GENRENAME="FANTASY">fantasy</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s book</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ludo and the Star Horse</TITLE>, <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>illustrated by <NAME>Gino D&apos;Achille</NAME>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="British Books, 1976" DBREF="46245">1976</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3796 (6 December 1974): 1386" DBREF="54246">3796 (6 December 1974): 1386</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The plot centres around the <TTHEMETOPIC>signs of the zodiac</TTHEMETOPIC>. <TCHARACTERNAME>Ludo</TCHARACTERNAME>, the protagonist, <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">falls into a <TTHEMETOPIC>crevasse in the snow</TTHEMETOPIC> while searching for his lost horse and lands in the House of Sagittarius. There he meets the Archer who tells him he can either return home or follow his horse, Renti, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">in search of his equine destiny through the perilous Star-Country of the Zodiac.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3796 (6 December 1974): 1386" DBREF="54246">3796 (6 December 1974): 1386</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">One reviewer noted that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the Star-Country has something real to say about life and death.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="TLS Archive 3796 (6 December 1974): 1386" DBREF="54246">3796 (6 December 1974): 1386</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>MS published her third and final <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">children&apos;s book</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Walk in Wolf Wood</TITLE>, in <DATE>1980</DATE>, <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>illustrated by <NAME>Doreen Caldwell</NAME>.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Non-Fiction Writing</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>Non-fiction writings by Stewart include two <TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">critical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">articles</TGENRE> for <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Writer</TITLE>: <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC"><TTHEMETOPIC>Setting and Background in the Novel</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, published in <DATE>December 1964</DATE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Teller of Tales</TITLE>, published in <DATE>May 1970</DATE>.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> Her <TGENRE GENRENAME="TRACTPAMPHLET">pamphlet</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">About Mary Stewart</TITLE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">offering information about herself</TGENRE>, appeared in 1973.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Friedman 8" DBREF="68611">8</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart" DBREF="68785"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION>In <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Teller of Tales</TITLE> she writes about her own works as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">light, fast-moving stories which are meant to give pleasure, and where the bees in the writer&apos;s bonnet are kept buzzing very softly indeed.</QUOTE> <TCHARACTERIZATION>Her protagonists, she says, are <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">averagely intelligent men and women who could be shocked or outraged into defending, if necessary with great physical bravery, what they held to be right.</QUOTE></TCHARACTERIZATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Stewart website" DBREF="69825" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Novels</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>While her Arthurian novel series and her forays in children&apos;s writing were still in progress, MS returned to her earlier genre of the <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">suspense <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE></TGENRE> with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Touch Not the Cat</TITLE>, published in <DATE>1976</DATE>. She also issued three more suspense novels: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Thornyhold</TITLE> (1988), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Stormy Petrel</TITLE> (1991), and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Rose Cottage</TITLE> (1997). All four, in contrast to many of her earlier suspense novels, are set in Britain (<TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Touch Not the Cat</TITLE> in <PLACE><REGION>Worcestershire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Stormy Petrel</TITLE>, like one of her earliest novels, in the <PLACE><REGION>Hebrides</REGION><GEOG REG="Scotland"></GEOG></PLACE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA online" DBREF="16185"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Stewart website" DBREF="69825"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Aspects of magic and the supernatural, which first appeared in the Arthurian novels, make an appearance in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Touch Not the Cat</TITLE> in the form of <TTHEMETOPIC>telepathy</TTHEMETOPIC> and as modern <TMOTIF>witchcraft</TMOTIF>  in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Thornyhold</TITLE>.</P><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Stormy Petrel</TITLE>, which is dedicated to the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Culcicoides Pulicaris Argyllensis</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Stormy prelims" DBREF="69847">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (the <TTHEMETOPIC>Scottish midge</TTHEMETOPIC>), delivers an <TTHEMETOPIC>environmental message</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Thornyhold</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="106216" PLACEHOLDER="MS, Thornyhold, 1988"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1 November 1988</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TGENREISSUE>In one of her latest <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">thrillers</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Thornyhold</TITLE>, MS took the conventions of a genre and subtly transmuted them.</TGENREISSUE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Blackwell" DBREF="579"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PDEDICATION>She dedicated this novel, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with love and gratitude,</QUOTE> to the memory of her parents.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Thornyhold, US ed, prelims" DBREF="69406">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The book is headed with a stanza from <NAME>George Meredith</NAME>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Enter these enchanted woods, / You who dare.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Thornyhold, US ed, prelims" DBREF="69406">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Ramsey, Gilly">Geillis, or Gilly, Ramsey</TCHARACTERNAME>, has a <TTHEMETOPIC>bleak and miserable childhood</TTHEMETOPIC> (in which some <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiographical</TGENRE> element, rendered into <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romance</TGENRE> form, is surely discernible). Her father, whom she adores, is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>harrassed, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rather saintly</QUOTE> Anglican vicar</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> with old-fashioned ideas about women. Her mother, who grew up in New Zealand, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">could have been a witch if she had chosen to,</QUOTE> but has dwindled into an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>English vicar&apos;s wife who <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">retained her <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="woman in power">dominance, her vivid personality, a hint of cruelty in her complete lack of sympathy for weakness or incompetence</TMOTIF>.</QUOTE></TCHARACTERTYPEROLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Thornyhold, US ed, 7" DBREF="69406">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> One bright spot is made by unpredictable visits from Cousin Geillis (after whom Gilly was named), who <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="witchcraft">shares her mother&apos;s witch-like quality, but in a manner that aims at pleasure</TMOTIF>, not power. Geillis gives Gilly a dog (which her parents give away when they send her to boarding school). <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">Years later, in 1948, after Gilly has <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="self-sacrifice">sacrificed her university career to care for her widowed father</TMOTIF>, and he has now died, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">Geillis dies too, leaving her a house in remote <PLACE><REGION>Wiltshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> called Thornyhold.</TMOTIF></TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE></P><P>Thornyhold turns out to have been the agent&apos;s house for a now <TTHEMETOPIC>ruined Georgian mansion</TTHEMETOPIC>. From the beginning Gilly loves it, as the first place she has ever called her own. She finds she loves <TTHEMETOPIC>housework</TTHEMETOPIC> here as well as <TTHEMETOPIC>gardening</TTHEMETOPIC>, and sets to work to make the place hers indeed. But there are odd off-key moments. A <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>helpful neighbour</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Agnes Trapp</TCHARACTERNAME>, seems to have expected an older woman as the new owner, and to have counted on bullying, managing, and taking advantage of her. Traces of Geillis&apos;s practice as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>herbalist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> remain, with some of the bottles labelled <SOCALLED>Poison</SOCALLED>. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="witchcraft">Gilly accepts food from Agnes and dreams vividly of a coven of witches; she begins to suspect Agnes of administering potions designed to work magic.</TMOTIF> She has strange experiences in which she seems briefly to take on the identity of her late cousin.</P><P>She strikes up a friendship with a small boy, William, falls in love with William&apos;s widowed father, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Dryden, Christopher">Christopher John Dryden</TCHARACTERNAME>, and <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rescue">rescues</TMOTIF> a <TTHEMETOPIC>tormented dog</TTHEMETOPIC>. It emerges gradually that Thornyhold has been a centre of white magic since the mid nineteenth century, when its occupant, the discarded wife of the squire, saw this as a defence against the bad magic emanating from her illicit successor in the big house. Agnes is indeed the centre of a local coven, which Cousin Geillis had steadfastly refused to join. Agnes, with the help of her son <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Trapp, Jessamy">Jessamy</TCHARACTERNAME>, was starving the dog because she was making a <TTHEMETOPIC>love philtre</TTHEMETOPIC> that called for hairs from <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a newly dead or dying dog.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Thornyhold, US ed, 160" DBREF="69406">160</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Agnes too is in love with Christopher Dryden, and it seems she can make a love philtre: she puts it in fudge, which she also eats herself. But no lasting harm is done&mdash;cruelty to animals remains the full extent of her wickedness. Christopher, who doesn&apos;t like fudge, passes it to a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>local shepherd</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="marriage ending">with whom Agnes then pairs up happily, leaving the way clear for Gilly and Christopher to do the same</TMOTIF>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Rose Cottage</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="70666" PLACEHOLDER="MS, Rose Cottage, 1997"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>5 June 1997</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY>MS&apos;s final book, another <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER"><TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romantic</TGENRE> suspense <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE></TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Rose Cottage</TITLE>, shared some of its preoccupations with <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Thornyhold</TITLE>.</PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Blackwell" DBREF="579"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">This story is set shortly after the second world war, in which its protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME>Kate Herrick</TCHARACTERNAME>, has been widowed. Kate grew up in her grandmother&apos;s home, Rose Cottage, in a village called Todhall in <PLACE><REGION>Cumbria</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE> She makes a visit back there before the projected sale of the cottage, and finds the peaceful village harbouring <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="witchcraft">rumours that some of the female inhabitants are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>witches</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></TMOTIF>. The <SOCALLED>witches</SOCALLED>, however, are instrumental in solving the more prosaic <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="mystery">mysteries</TMOTIF> of the place.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Poetry</HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="69306" PLACEHOLDER="MS, Frost on the Window and Other Poems, 1990"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>15 November 1990</DATE><CHRONPROSE>MS published a collection of <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Frost on the Window and Other Poems</TITLE>, <PDEDICATION>dedicated to her <NAME STANDARD="Stewart, Sir Frederick Henry">husband</NAME></PDEDICATION> and <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>embellished with charming landscape sketches.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Blackwell" DBREF="579"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="MS, Frost, prelims" DBREF="69306">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The collection included poems MS had written before she began writing novels as well as poems from her Merlin novels. <PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>In her preface she wrote that her poetry <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lay forgotten for many years</QUOTE> before it occurred to her to try to save some of if from oblivion.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Stewart website" DBREF="69825"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY> <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>The four pieces already printed in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Durham University Journal</TITLE> include an extended sequence.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><PNONBOOKMEDIA>The collection was published in audio book form in 1991.</PNONBOOKMEDIA></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>These are highly literary poems. In her preface MS invokes <NAME STANDARD="Keats, John">Keats</NAME>. She writes on mythological topics, both Biblical (<TCHARACTERNAME>Eve</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Cain</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Mary,, the mother of Jesus">Mary</TCHARACTERNAME>) and classical (<TCHARACTERNAME>Icarus</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Persephone</TCHARACTERNAME>). She titles poems with an eye to her predecessors, addresses <NAME>Louis Aragon</NAME> on the fall of Paris, or writes an answer to <NAME STANDARD="Marvell, Andrew">Marvell</NAME> from his coy mistress (suggesting that he should stick with plants instead of attempting the more challenging love of a human woman). Some poems aim at <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="supernatural">haunting</TMOTIF> effects. <TVOICENARRATION>The male speaker in <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Circle</TITLE>, having pricked his finger, draws a circle in blood and stands within it, watching as a procession of maidens one by one appears before him and then vanishes. When the last one makes as if to stay, he <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">from out the circle stept, / And laughed, and went upon my way.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Stewart website" DBREF="69825" QTDIN="QTDINYES"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TVOICENARRATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Rochelle Ratner</NAME>, reviewing for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Library Journal</TITLE>, was on the whole disparaging about these poems.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Ratner, Library Journal 116 (1 September 1991): 254" DBREF="70745">116 (1 Septemeber 1991): 254</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>The Writing Process</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>MS&apos;s novels took anywhere <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">from twelve to eighteen months to write.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wilson Library Bulletin 35 (December 1960): 328" DBREF="68765" QTDIN="QTDINYES">35 (December 1960): 328</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>As part of the writing process she kept regular hours: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The early or most difficult stages are done in short bursts&mdash;four hours&apos; writing or 2,000 words per day . . . . Towards the end of a book it is so alive and all-consuming for me that I find it hard to stop writing.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 9" DBREF="68785">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> By the 1970s, MS had developed a routine which involved spending time in the morning doing chores, casual writing, and answering correspondence (for which she eventually hired a secretary to help). Then in the afternoon she would write seriously. Though she stopped to make dinner, she would sometimes continue to write in the evenings.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 9" DBREF="68785">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>Each novel was re-written three times, and the final and fourth draft was then given a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">polish  and overhaul.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 9" DBREF="68785">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The first draft usually took three to four months, and was half-written, half-dictated. This resulted in a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rough working outline of the novel,</QUOTE> which was then rewritten <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">chapter by chapter</QUOTE> over the next six months.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 10" DBREF="68785">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>Her first success frightened her, and when she first saw a photo of herself displayed <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">with a <QUOTE DIRECT="N">new writer</QUOTE> caption underneath,</QUOTE> she burst into tears. The fear recurred later, when she had a reputation to keep up.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 567" DBREF="68970">567</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Literary Influences</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>MS is bored by modern movements like the anti-novel, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the sicks and the beats,</QUOTE> but feels there was a place for them: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">they&apos;re trying things out, keeping literature alive and moving.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 561" DBREF="68970">561</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TCHARACTERIZATION>She thinks her age needs <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a hero, a hero-pattern&mdash;not the old type flag-waving-stiff-upper-lip hero, but some living pattern of rightness that fits our time.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 565" DBREF="68970">565</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION> The list of writers she admires is eclectic: <NAME>Graham Greene</NAME>, <NAME>J. D. Salinger</NAME>, <NAME>James Baldwin</NAME>, <NAME>Pamela Hansford Johnson</NAME>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 568" DBREF="68970">568</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and many other popular novelists (including <NAME>Ian Fleming</NAME>, though she feared he was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">getting farther and farther out on a limb for plots</QUOTE>) and playwrights.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 569" DBREF="68970">569</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She is sceptical of categorizing books (into, for instance, popular and high culture), recognizing <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">only two kinds of novels, badly written and well written.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 564" DBREF="68970">564</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Critical Reception</HEADING><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Reviews of MS&apos;s novels have varied, although as Stewart puts it, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[o]n the whole, reviewers have been very kind</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newquist 566" DBREF="68970">566</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Hemmings, Frederick William John">F. W. J. Hemmings</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Mary Queen of Hearts</TITLE>, published in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New Statesman</TITLE> in <DATE>1956</DATE>, was the first to provide a literary analysis.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mussell, Woman&apos;s Gothic and Romantic Fiction 37" DBREF="69151">37</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He noted that her success was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">well earned, for there is nothing cheap in the writing and nothing machine-made in the devising.</QUOTE> In conclusion he pronounced her writings to be the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">genuine triumphs of a minor art.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New Statesman 70 (5 November 1956): 699" DBREF="4861">70 (5 November 1956): 699</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRECOGNITIONS>In <DATE>1968</DATE>, to her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">great pleasure</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About Mary Stewart 11" DBREF="68785">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>MS was elected <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Fellow of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Royal Society for the Encouragement of Arts,, Manufactures and Commerce">Royal Society of Arts</ORGNAME></RRECOGNITIONNAME>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="About the Author 217" DBREF="68786">217</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE"><DATE>3 July 2009</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RRECOGNITIONS>MS was awarded the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>honorary degree of Doctor of Letters</RRECOGNITIONNAME> by <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Durham">Durham University</ORGNAME>, her alma mater, at a ceremony in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Durham Cathedral</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Durham"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Durham"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</RRECOGNITIONS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Hutchison" DBREF="68791"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The degree was awarded as part of the celebrations for the hundred and fiftieth anniversary of the founding of the <ORGNAME>University of Durham</ORGNAME>. The speech introducing MS at the ceremony was given by Professor <NAME>Chris Hutchison</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Hutchison" DBREF="68791"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Recently her Arthurian novels in particular have attracted scholarly attention, resulting in studies and dissertations.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">The popular appeal of her romantic suspense novels is reflected in the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">unofficial Mary Stewart website</QUOTE> maintained by two sisters in <PLACE><REGION>North Carolina</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, who inherited their passion for Stewart&apos;s books from their mother and felt that a website would be a less creepy alternative to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">build[ing] a shrine to Mary Stewart in our living room.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mary Stewart website" DBREF="69825"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Newquist, Roy. Counterpoint. 1965.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Stewart, Mary. The Wicked Day. 1983.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Stewart, Mary. Thornyhold. 1988</SOURCE><SOURCE>Stewart, Mary. Three Novels of Suspense. 69846</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>